  "preview": "Conversation on March 1: — When is your release? — March 15. Conversation on April 1: — When is your release? — April 15. — But it was supposed to be March 15 — When we tried to release, we discovered",
  "text": "Conversation on March 1:\n— 𝘞𝘩𝘦𝘯 𝘪𝘴 𝘺𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘳𝘦𝘭𝘦𝘢𝘴𝘦?\n— 𝘔𝘢𝘳𝘤𝘩 15.\n\nConversation on April 1:\n— 𝘞𝘩𝘦𝘯 𝘪𝘴 𝘺𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘳𝘦𝘭𝘦𝘢𝘴𝘦?\n— 𝘈𝘱𝘳𝘪𝘭 15.\n— 𝘉𝘶𝘵 𝘪𝘵 𝘸𝘢𝘴 𝘴𝘶𝘱𝘱𝘰𝘴𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘰 𝘣𝘦 𝘔𝘢𝘳𝘤𝘩 15 🤔\n— 𝘞𝘩𝘦𝘯 𝘸𝘦 𝘵𝘳𝘪𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘰 𝘳𝘦𝘭𝘦𝘢𝘴𝘦, 𝘸𝘦 𝘥𝘪𝘴𝘤𝘰𝘷𝘦𝘳𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘩𝘢𝘵 𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘴𝘰𝘭𝘶𝘵𝘪𝘰𝘯 𝘤𝘰𝘶𝘭𝘥 𝘯𝘰𝘵 𝘣𝘦 𝘥𝘦𝘱𝘭𝘰𝘺𝘦𝘥 𝘵𝘰 𝘵𝘩𝘦 𝘳𝘦𝘲𝘶𝘪𝘳𝘦𝘥 𝘱𝘭𝘢𝘵𝘧𝘰𝘳𝘮. 𝘕𝘰𝘸 𝘸𝘦’𝘳𝘦 𝘳𝘦𝘣𝘶𝘪𝘭𝘥𝘪𝘯𝘨 𝘪𝘵.\n\nI see 𝘁𝘄𝗼 𝘁𝗼 𝘁𝗵𝗿𝗲𝗲 𝗰𝗮𝘀𝗲𝘀 𝗹𝗶𝗸𝗲 𝘁𝗵𝗶𝘀 𝗲𝘃𝗲𝗿𝘆 𝘆𝗲𝗮𝗿.\n\nEngineers are naturally wired to focus on the code — and honestly, that's exactly what's expected of them. So they optimize, refactor, polish... and from my experience, they often skip the one thing that would have saved them months.\n\n𝗔 𝘀𝗶𝗺𝗽𝗹𝗲 𝗛𝗲𝗹𝗹𝗼 𝗪𝗼𝗿𝗹𝗱 𝗱𝗲𝗽𝗹𝗼𝘆𝗲𝗱 𝗶𝗻 𝘄𝗲𝗲𝗸 𝗼𝗻𝗲.🤔\n\nIt sounds obvious when you say it out loud. From what I've seen though, it quietly forces the team to shift how they think about \"done.\" Because a product, unlike a project, has no final done — it's an endless process of improving and making it valuable.\n\n𝗣𝗿𝗼𝗷𝗲𝗰𝘁 𝗺𝗶𝗻𝗱𝘀𝗲𝘁: \"When will this be finished and deployed?\"\n𝗣𝗿𝗼𝗱𝘂𝗰𝘁 𝗺𝗶𝗻𝗱𝘀𝗲𝘁: \"How do we deploy more often to keep improving this?\" 🚀\n\nThe earlier you taste that in practice, the less time you might lose rebuilding things that were never going to deploy anyway. 🎯\n\n𝘏𝘰𝘸 𝘥𝘰𝘦𝘴 𝘺𝘰𝘶𝘳 𝘵𝘦𝘢𝘮 𝘵𝘩𝘪𝘯𝘬 𝘢𝘣𝘰𝘶𝘵 𝘥𝘦𝘱𝘭𝘰𝘺𝘮𝘦𝘯𝘵 — 𝘢𝘴 𝘢 𝘧𝘪𝘯𝘪𝘴𝘩 𝘭𝘪𝘯𝘦 𝘰𝘳 𝘢𝘴 𝘢 𝘳𝘩𝘺𝘵𝘩𝘮?",
